8) Identify H.
That's right! At the distal radioulnar joint (H) the head of ulna articulates with ulnar notch of radius. This joint participates in pronation and supination of the forearm.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Now that you understand that the head of the ulna is isolated from the proximal row of carpal bones, the proper name of the wrist joint will make sense to you. It is the radiocarpal joint. The ulna does not figure into the name, because the ulna does not participate in the articulation.

two prosections of the wrist and hand. One is sectioned in the coronal plane, the other is sectioned horizontally through the radiocarpal (wrist) joint. 
On the prosection split in the coronal plane, identify the distal radius and the head of the ulna. Look for the fibrocartilagenous disc extending across the distal end of the ulna. Notice that a coronal section through the wrist demonstrates that the distal radioulnar joint space is L-shaped (red arrow). Confirm that the fibrocartilagenous disc does, indeed, exclude the ulna from articulating with the proximal row of carpal bones.
